<!-- wp:list -->

<ul><li><strong>A new study reveals stark differences in how male and female cancer patients are counseled about the sexual side effects of treatment.</strong></li><li><strong>The research compared patients with various types of genitourinary cancer and found that only one in 10 women was asked about their sexual health, compared to nine in 10 men.</strong></li><li><strong>Brachytherapy is a common and highly effective treatment for genitourinary cancer, but nearly 90% of women and 50% of men experience sexual dysfunction afterward.</strong></li></ul>

<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p>According to new research, the vast majority of female patients undergoing cancer treatment are not counseled about the sexual side effects they may experience during or after treatment.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p>The report, which will be&nbsp;<a href="https://plan.core-apps.com/myastroapp2022/abstract/f292dd93-0489-4e15-9bdd-1f31e93fe12d" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">presented</a>&nbsp;at the&nbsp;<a href="https://www.astro.org/annualmeeting" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">American Society for Radiation Oncology (ASTRO) Annual Meeting</a>&nbsp;Tuesday, found that only one in 10 women with genitourinary cancer were asked about their sexual health, compared to nine in 10 men.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p><a href="https://cancer.dartmouth.edu/prostate/genitourinary-cancers-tests-and-treatments" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Genitourinary cancers</a>&nbsp;impact the urinary system and reproductive organs.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p>The researchers believe sexual dysfunction is discussed more frequently with male patients because there are more treatment options and remedies for sexual dysfunction for those with prostate cancer compared to those with cervical cancer.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p>Furthermore, many physicians are likely more comfortable discussing sexual health with male patients, the researchers said in a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.astro.org/News-and-Publications/News-and-Media-Center/News-Releases/2022/Sexual-side-effects-of-cancer-treatment-often-unad" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">press release</a>.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p>Approximately 13,000 cases of cervical cancer and more than 220,000 cases of prostate cancer are diagnosed each year, and because brachytherapy — the internal radiation therapy used for genitourinary cancers — is so effective, most patients live a long life.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p><a href="https://www.healthline.com/health/cervical-cancer/brachytherapy-cervical-cancer">Brachytherapy</a>&nbsp;is known to cause sexual side effects in most patients, and as this study shows, many aren’t properly counseled on how to alleviate those symptoms.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->

<p>“I think that all oncologists should ask about women’s sexual function after any diagnosis of gynecological cancers, and I hope papers like this one will encourage that process,”&nbsp;<a href="https://www.yalemedicine.org/specialists/maryjane_minkin" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dr. Mary Jane Minkin</a>, the co-director of Yale Medicine’s&nbsp;<a href="https://www.yalemedicine.org/news/sex-intimacy-after-cancer" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Sexual Intimacy &amp; Menopause Program</a>, told Healthline.</p>

<!-- /wp:paragraph -->
